</math></span><img src="assets/bd70cc2fdee27ca892a2742fafc9827e" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:33.61ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \quad k(\varphi )\;=\;{\frac {P&#039;M&#039;}{PM}}\;=\;{\frac {\delta x}{R\cos \varphi \,\delta \lambda }},}"/></span></dd>
<dd><i>meridian scale factor</i>&#160;&#160; <span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle \quad h(\varphi )\;=\;{\frac {P'K'}{PK}}\;=\;{\frac {\delta y}{R\delta \varphi \,}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mspace width="1em" />
        <mi>h</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mspace width="thickmathspace" />
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mspace width="thickmathspace" />
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <msup>
                <mi>P</mi>
                <mo>&#x2032;</mo>
              </msup>
              <msup>
                <mi>K</mi>
                <mo>&#x2032;</mo>
              </msup>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>P</mi>
              <mi>K</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width="thickmathspace" />
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mspace width="thickmathspace" />
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>&#x03B4;<!-- δ --></mi>
              <mi>y</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>R</mi>
              <mi>&#x03B4;<!-- δ --></mi>
              <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
              <mspace width="thinmathspace" />
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \quad h(\varphi )\;=\;{\frac {P'K'}{PK}}\;=\;{\frac {\delta y}{R\delta \varphi \,}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="assets/c2c8a1c5549242da38bd303beb31c690" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:28.092ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \quad h(\varphi )\;=\;{\frac {P&#039;K&#039;}{PK}}\;=\;{\frac {\delta y}{R\delta \varphi \,}}.}"/></span></dd></dl>
<p>Since the meridians are mapped to lines of constant <i>x</i>, we must have <span class="nowrap"><i>x</i> = <i>R</i>(<i>λ</i> − <i>λ</i><sub>0</sub>)</span> and <i>δx</i>&#160;=&#160;<i>Rδλ</i>, (<i>λ</i> in radians). Therefore, in the limit of infinitesimally small elements
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle \tan \beta ={\frac {R\sec \varphi }{y'(\varphi )}}\tan \alpha \,,\qquad k=\sec \varphi \,,\qquad h={\frac {y'(\varphi )}{R}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>tan</mi>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mi>&#x03B2;<!-- β --></mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>R</mi>
              <mi>sec</mi>
              <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
              <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <msup>
                <mi>y</mi>
                <mo>&#x2032;</mo>
              </msup>
              <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
              <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
              <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mi>tan</mi>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mi>&#x03B1;<!-- α --></mi>
        <mspace width="thinmathspace" />
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mspace width="2em" />
        <mi>k</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>sec</mi>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mspace width="thinmathspace" />
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mspace width="2em" />
        <mi>h</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <msup>
                <mi>y</mi>
                <mo>&#x2032;</mo>
              </msup>
              <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
              <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
              <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>R</mi>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \tan \beta ={\frac {R\sec \varphi }{y'(\varphi )}}\tan \alpha \,,\qquad k=\sec \varphi \,,\qquad h={\frac {y'(\varphi )}{R}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="assets/59e1fb3573a0521dafde333eaf0f1f93" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.671ex; width:54.1ex; height:6.509ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \tan \beta ={\frac {R\sec \varphi }{y&#039;(\varphi )}}\tan \alpha \,,\qquad k=\sec \varphi \,,\qquad h={\frac {y&#039;(\varphi )}{R}}.}"/></span></dd></dl>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Derivation_of_the_Mercator_projection">Derivation of the Mercator projection</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercator_projection&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Derivation of the Mercator projection">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The choice of the function <i>y</i>(<i>φ</i>) for the Mercator projection is determined by the demand that the projection be conformal, a condition which can be defined in two equivalent ways:
</p>
<dl><dd><ul><li><i>Equality of angles</i>. The condition that a sailing course of constant azimuth <i>&#945;</i> on the globe is mapped into a constant grid bearing <i>β</i> on the map. Setting <i>α</i>&#160;=&#160;<i>β</i> in the above equations gives <i>y&#8239;′</i>(<i>φ</i>)&#160;=&#160;<i>R</i>&#160;sec&#160;<i>φ</i>.</li>
<li><i>Isotropy of scale factors</i>. This is the statement that the point scale factor is independent of direction so that small shapes are preserved by the projection. Setting <i>h</i>&#160;=&#160;<i>k</i> in the above equations again gives <i>y&#8239;′</i>(<i>φ</i>)&#160;=&#160;<i>R</i>&#160;sec&#160;<i>φ</i>.</li></ul></dd></dl>
<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercator_y_plot.svg" class="image"><img alt="Mercator y plot.svg" src="assets/66db14e9f3893ac004e5ea92f01d15e7.png" decoding="async" width="154" height="232" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Mercator_y_plot.svg/231px-Mercator_y_plot.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Mercator_y_plot.svg/308px-Mercator_y_plot.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="154" data-file-height="232" /></a></div>
<p>Integrating the equation
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle y'(\varphi )=R\sec \varphi ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <msup>
          <mi>y</mi>
          <mo>&#x2032;</mo>
        </msup>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>R</mi>
        <mi>sec</mi>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle y'(\varphi )=R\sec \varphi ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="assets/3a8353aa4168c6516036773a04f5da4e" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:15.959ex; height:3.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle y&#039;(\varphi )=R\sec \varphi ,}"/></span></dd></dl>
<p>with <i>y</i>(0)&#160;=&#160;0, by using <a href="/wiki/Integral_table" class="mw-redirect" title="Integral table">integral tables</a><sup id="cite_ref-gudermannian_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gudermannian-21">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> or <a href="/wiki/Integral_of_the_secant_function" title="Integral of the secant function">elementary methods</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-osborne_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-osborne-22">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> gives y(φ). Therefore,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle x=R(\lambda -\lambda _{0}),\qquad y=R\ln \left[\tan \left({\frac {\pi }{4}}+{\frac {\varphi }{2}}\right)\right].}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>R</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>&#x03BB;<!-- λ --></mi>
        <mo>&#x2212;<!-- − --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>&#x03BB;<!-- λ --></mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mspace width="2em" />
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>R</mi>
        <mi>ln</mi>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mrow>
          <mo>[</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mi>tan</mi>
            <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mrow>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mi>&#x03C0;<!-- π --></mi>
                    <mn>4</mn>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo>]</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x=R(\lambda -\lambda _{0}),\qquad y=R\ln \left[\tan \left({\frac {\pi }{4}}+{\frac {\varphi }{2}}\right)\right].}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="assets/bd9afa5129eaa969535f2e0aa177be3d" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.838ex; width:44.972ex; height:4.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle x=R(\lambda -\lambda _{0}),\qquad y=R\ln \left[\tan \left({\frac {\pi }{4}}+{\frac {\varphi }{2}}\right)\right].}"/></span></dd></dl>
<p>In the first equation <i>λ</i><sub>0</sub> is the longitude of an arbitrary central meridian usually, but not always, that of Greenwich (i.e., zero). The difference (<i>λ</i>&#160;−&#160;<i>λ</i><sub>0</sub>) is in radians.
</p><p>The function <i>y</i>(<i>φ</i>) is plotted alongside <i>φ</i> for the case <i>R</i>&#160;=&#160;1: it tends to infinity at the poles. The linear <i>y</i>-axis values are not usually shown on printed maps; instead some maps show the non-linear scale of latitude values on the right. More often than not the maps show only a graticule of selected meridians and parallels
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Inverse_transformations">Inverse transformations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercator_projection&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Inverse transformations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle \lambda =\lambda _{0}+{\frac {x}{R}},\qquad \varphi =2\tan ^{-1}\left[\exp \left({\frac {y}{R}}\right)\right]-{\frac {\pi }{2}}\,.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>&#x03BB;<!-- λ --></mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>&#x03BB;<!-- λ --></mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>x</mi>
            <mi>R</mi>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mspace width="2em" />
        <mi>&#x03C6;<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <msup>
          <mi>tan</mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>&#x2212;<!-- − --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mrow>
          <mo>[</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mi>exp</mi>
            <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mfrac>
                  <mi>y</mi>
                  <mi>R</mi>
                </mfrac>
              </mrow>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo>]</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>&#x2212;<!-- − --></mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>&#x03C0;<!-- π --></mi>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width="thinmathspace" />
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \lambda =\lambda _{0}+{\frac {x}{R}},\qquad \varphi =2\tan ^{-1}\left[\exp \left({\frac {y}{R}}\right)\right]-{\frac {\pi }{2}}\,.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="assets/7506adfac1bbfee0c17656da1a80172f" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.005ex; width:47.009ex; height:5.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \lambda =\lambda _{0}+{\frac {x}{R}},\qquad \varphi =2\tan ^{-1}\left[\exp \left({\frac {y}{R}}\right)\right]-{\frac {\pi }{2}}\,.}"/></span></dd></dl>
<p>The expression on the right of the second equation defines the <a href="/wiki/Gudermannian_function" title="Gudermannian function">Gudermannian function</a>; i.e., <i>φ</i>&#160;=&#160;gd(<span role="math" class="sfrac nowrap tion" style="display:inline-block; vertical-align:-0.5em; font-size:85%; text-align:center;"><span class="num" style="display:block; line-height:1em; margin:0 0.1em;"><i>y</i></span><span class="slash visualhide">/</span><span class="den" style="display:block; line-height:1em; margin:0 0.1em; border-top:1px solid;"><i>R</i></span></span>): the direct equation may therefore be written as <i>y</i>&#160;=&#160;<i>R</i>·gd<sup>−1</sup>(<i>φ</i>).<sup id="cite_ref-gudermannian_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gudermannian-21">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Alternative_expressions">Alternative expressions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercator_projection&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Alternative expressions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>There are many alternative expressions for <i>y</i>(<i>φ</i>), all derived by elementary manipulations.<sup id="cite_ref-osborne_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-osborne-22">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}y&amp;=&amp;{\frac {R}{2}}\ln \left[{\frac {1+\sin \varphi }{1-\sin \varphi }}\right]&amp;=&amp;{R}\ln \left[{\frac {1+\sin \varphi }{\cos \varphi }}\right]&amp;=R\ln \left(\sec \varphi +\tan \varphi \right)\\[2ex]&amp;=&amp;R\tanh ^{-1}\left(\sin \varphi \right)&amp;=&amp;R\sinh ^{-1}\left(\tan \varphi \right)&amp;=R\operatorname {sgn} (\varphi )\cosh ^{-1}\left(\sec \varphi \right)=R\operatorname {gd} ^{-1}(\varphi ).\end{aligned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="1.16em 0.3em" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true">
