<p>The above formulae are written in terms of the globe radius <i>R</i>. It is often convenient to work directly with the map width <i>W</i>&#160;=&#160;2<span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">π</span><i>R</i>. For example, the basic transformation equations become
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="assets/03dc2db4ac34a8b7adc2f4095fed2fb9"  alttext="{\displaystyle x={\frac {W}{2\pi }}\left(\lambda -\lambda _{0}\right),\qquad \quad y={\frac {W}{2\pi }}\ln \left[\tan \left({\frac {\pi }{4}}+{\frac {\varphi }{2}}\right)\right].}">
