<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercator_projection&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">A generator of a cylinder is a straight line on the surface parallel to the axis of the cylinder.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The function <i>y</i>(<i>φ</i>) is not completely arbitrary: it must be monotonic increasing and antisymmetric (<i>y</i>(−<i>φ</i>)&#160;=&#160;−<i>y</i>(<i>φ</i>), so that <i>y</i>(0)=0): it is normally continuous with a continuous first derivative.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>R</i> is the radius of the globe and <i>φ</i> is measured in radians.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>λ</i> is measured in radians.&lt;/ref&gt; The corresponding points on the projection define a rectangle of width&#160;<i>δx</i> and height&#160;<i>δy</i>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">More general example of Tissot's indicatrix: the <a href="/wiki/Scale_(map)#Visualisation_of_point_scale:_the_Tissot_indicatrix" title="Scale (map)">Winkel tripel</a> projection.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See <a href="/wiki/Great-circle_distance" title="Great-circle distance">great-circle distance</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Vincenty%27s_formulae" title="Vincenty&#39;s formulae">Vincenty's formulae</a>, or <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/GreatCircle.html">Mathworld</a>.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
